     {
       "category": "governance",
       "content": "Section 7.3 of DC CAP's AI Governance Framework names the line every pilot member is accountable to: \"All external communications remain staff-authored; Claude is a tool in the drafting process.\" Section 7.2 backs it: \"Staff remain accountable for the quality and accuracy of all work product.\" Those two sentences carry the pilot's deepest expectation. The author is the person whose name appears on the email, the proposal, the report. Claude drafts. The author signs.\n\nThe expectation becomes operational this week. In Week 4 you trade work with a colleague. They will read what you sent and tell you what they noticed. The feedback runs deeper when the draft already passed through your hands. A forwarded first output makes your colleague your QA layer. The peer review collapses into proofreading.\n\nThe verification pass has three checks. Check the facts first. Every claim about scholar outcomes, partner counts, deadlines, or policy must trace to a source you can cite. Check the voice second. Claude can match a tone and also smooth your edges into someone else's. Check the standard third. Read each sentence as if you were defending it in a board meeting or in a parent conversation. That is the bar the framework sets when it puts staff signatures on work product.\n\nThe framework treats Claude as a drafting accelerant. The deliverable carries your signature. Walk every output through the verification pass before it leaves your screen. That makes the peer feedback you get this week an audit of your judgment.",
